h Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sydenham,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Sydenham in Bridgwater (Somerset), Sydenham Damerel (Devon), and Sydenham (Oxon)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Titchmarsh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Titchmarsh (Northants), which is recorded as  <i>Titemerse</i> in 1206. The surname became associated by folk etymology with the word  <i>titmouse</i> (Middle English  <i>titmose</i>), denoting a small songbird. There may have been some confusion with   Tidmarsh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Titmarsh","meanings":["English:  see  Titchmarsh  ."]},{"name":"Titmas","meanings":["English:  see  Titchmarsh  ."]},{"name":"Tidmarsh","meanings":["English: habitational name from Tidmarsh in Berkshire, which is named from Old English <i>thēod</i> ‘people’ + <i>mersc</i> ‘marsh’."]},{"name":"Titmus","meanings":["English (Hertfordshire): variant of <b>Titchmarsh</b>, a habitational name from Titchmarsh in Northamptonshire. The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Ticcea</i> + Old English <i>mersc</i> ‘marsh’. The surname became associated by folk etymology with the word <i>titmouse</i> (Middle English <i>titmose</i>), denoting a small songbird. There may have been some confusion with   Tidmarsh  ."]},{"name":"Titmuss","meanings":["English:  see  Titchmarsh  ."]},{"name":"Titchmarch","meanings":["English:  see  Titchmarsh  ."]},{"name":"Titmass","meanings":["English:  see  Titchmarsh  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Arch